Recipe 1: Genfo (Porridge)
Genfo means “thick porridge” in the ancient African language of Amharic.
Most people make it using barley flour, wheat flour or corn meal. Each type
offers its own great taste.
Yield: 3-4 Servings
Preparation Time: 50 minutes
Ingredient List:
1 teaspoon of berbere spice mixture
2 tablespoons Kibbeh (seasoned, clarified butter, also called
kibe)
2 cups flour, all-purpose
Water, purified
Salt, coarse
HHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHH
Preparation:
1. Add 3 cups water and 1 teaspoon salt to medium sized pot. Bring to boil
over med-high.
2. When water is boiling, add flour slowly. Stir with wooden spoon. You
will notice that the flour will cause it to be quite thick, and difficult to stir.
3. Continue stirring to remove lumps. Mix hard. Add extra water if needed.
4. Remove water and flour, now a porridge called genfo, from heat. Add the
melted butter to a bowl. Scoop genfo in a ball into bowl.
5. In center of ball of genfo, create a well with a spoon. Add berbere and
melted kibe butter while it is still hot. Mix well. Serve.
Recipe 2: Firfir & Egg
This firfir dish is pretty easy to bring together. If you make your sauce the
previous night, you can rewarm it when you’re ready to eat, and throw the
bread in. It’s a hearty, spicy, delicious breakfast treat.
Yield: 2-4 Servings
Preparation Time: 35 minutes
Ingredient List:
4 minced garlic cloves
1 tablespoon of oil, olive
½ minced small onion, yellow
2 eggs, large
2 cups of torn baguettes
1 & ½ cups of stock, vegetable
1 tablespoon of tomato paste
1 & ½ tablespoons of berbere spice (African spice mixture), +
more as desired
½ teaspoons of salt, kosher
Optional:
Sliced cucumbers, to serve
2 tablespoons of yogurt, plain, to serve
¾ cup of chick peas
HHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHH
Preparation:
1. Sauté salt and onion in large sized fry pan over med. heat until onion
becomes soft and translucent. Add tomato paste, garlic and berbere spices.
Stir together. Add in beans and water and stir again.
2. Increase the heat up to high and bring to boil. Then lower the heat to hold
the simmer. Leave uncovered and cook for 10 minutes or so. The sauce
should be reduced by 1/3.
3. Taste for seasoning and add some more berbere, as desired.
4. Keep sauce warmed on low flame while cooking eggs. Cook them the
way you prefer. Sunny side up works well, since the runny yolk goes great
with spicy sauce.
5. When eggs are nearly done, stir bread into sauce. Spoon it into two
individual bowls. Top bowls with one egg each. Dollop yogurt on top of
bowls. Serve promptly.
