Recipe 28: Ethiopian Fruit Salad
From baklava, which is very labor intensive, we come now to fruit salad,
which is simplicity in recipe form. It includes fresh fruit – that’s it. Be sure
everything else is ready before you peel the bananas.
Yield: 6 Servings
Preparation Time: 15 minutes
Ingredient List:
1 sliced banana
1 & ½ cups of grapes, seedless
1 orange with peel removed, then cut into sections
1 peeled, cubed papaya, ripe, small
1 peeled, cubed mango, ripe
HHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHH
Preparation:
1. Combine the sliced and cubed fruits. Add banana just before serving.
Serve.
Recipe 29: Ethiopian Baklava
Baklava in Ethiopia? Yep! It is made in many countries in the region
Ethiopia shares with others.  This recipe includes a thick syrup, and it is
wildly popular, since desserts are not common in Ethiopia.
Yield: 1-2 Servings
Preparation Time: 2 hours and 10 minutes
Ingredient List:
¼ cup of water, distilled
1 cup of flour, all-purpose
1/5 tablespoons of salt, coarse
2 eggs, medium
1 & 1/3 cups of starch
1 teaspoon of oil, olive
For the filling:
1 & ½ cups of walnuts, ground
1 cup of margarine, melted
For the syrup:
2 cups of water, distilled
2 cups of sugar, granulated
2 teaspoons of juice, lemon
HHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHH
Preparation:
1. Prepare dough using recipe on flour package.
2. Place pieces of dough on wooden board atop each other.
3. Cut pieces using cooking tray size as gauge.
4. Lightly grease tray. Place ½ of dough pieces on tray. There should only
be one layer. Pour margarine over them.
5. When you have used ½ of dough, sprinkle a layer of walnuts over top of
it.
6. After the walnuts, make another dough layer. Spread with margarine.
Add another dough layer and margarine. Continue until all dough has been
used.
7. Cut dough pieces in baklava shapes. Place in oven on medium
temperature. Cook for one hour. They should appear golden and brown.
Remove from oven.
8. Place lemon juice, sugar and water in a pan. Melt sugar on med. heat on
stove top burner. Boil for 15 minutes or so until mixture has a syrup-y
consistency.
9. Remove syrup from burner. Brush baklava with butter and pour syrup on
top. Place on serving plate or pan and serve.
Recipe 30: Sanbusa Turnovers
Picture, if you will, an Indian samosa. That is somewhat like this dish, but
sanbusa is lighter and smaller, with a tasty, sweet filling. They are earthy,
yet still delicate, with a shell that is crispy thin and a yummy filling.
Yield: 10+ Servings
Preparation Time: 1 hour & 55 minutes
Ingredient List:
For the dough:
½ to ¾ cup of water, distilled, cold
2 teaspoons of sea salt, coarse
5 cups of flour, white
¾ cup of oil, olive
¾ cup of butter, unsalted
For the sweet filling:
2 tablespoons of rose water
1 tablespoon of water, distilled, with ¼ teaspoons of saffron
dissolved in it
2 teaspoons of cardamom
1 & ½ cups of sugar, granulated
3 cups of ground walnuts
HHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHHH
Preparation:
To make the dough
1. Melt butter in oil.
2. Combine salt & flour in medium bowl. Create a shallow well in center.
Add butter and oil into well.
3. Vigorously stir till well combined. Add water until dough is holding
together and pulling away from bowl sides a bit.
4. Wrap dough ball in cling wrap. Allow to set in fridge while you prepare
filling.
To make the sweet filling:
5. Combine ingredients. Stir well.
To assemble Sanbusa:
6. Preheat oven to 350F.
7. Use a walnut-sized dough piece for each pastry. Roll into 3” circles.
8. Place 1 teaspoon of sweet filling into center of dough circles. Fold them
into half-moons. Firmly pinch edges.
9. Place pastries on ungreased cookie sheet. Bake in oven for 45 minutes.
They should appear yellow-gold in color. Serve while warm. 
About the Author
Angel Burns learned to cook when she worked in the local seafood
restaurant near her home in Hyannis Port in Massachusetts as a teenager.
The head chef took Angel under his wing and taught the young woman the
tricks of the trade for cooking seafood. The skills she had learned at a
young age helped her get accepted into Boston University’s Culinary
Program where she also minored in business administration.
Summers off from school meant working at the same restaurant but when
Angel’s mentor and friend retired as head chef, she took over after
graduation and created classic and new dishes that delighted the diners. The
restaurant flourished under Angel’s culinary creativity and one customer
developed more than an appreciation for Angel’s food. Several months after
taking over the position, the young woman met her future husband at work
and they have been inseparable ever since.  They still live in Hyannis Port
with their two children and a cocker spaniel named Buddy.
Angel Burns turned her passion for cooking and her business acumen into a
thriving e-book business. She has authored several successful books on
cooking different types of dishes using simple ingredients for novices and
experienced chefs alike. She is still head chef in Hyannis Port and says she
will probably never leave!
